# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: preboot-execution-environment
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Internally, ACPI advertises the available components and their functions to the operating system kernel using instruction lists ("methods") provided through the system firmware (UEFI or BIOS), which the kernel parses.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] ACPI then executes the desired operations written in *ACPI Machine Language* (such as the initialization of hardware components) using an embedded minimal virtual machine.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Intel, Microsoft and Toshiba originally developed the standard, while HP, Huawei and Phoenix also participated later.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] In October 2013, ACPI Special Interest Group (ACPI SIG), the original developers of the ACPI standard, agreed to transfer all assets to the UEFI Forum, in which all future development will take place.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] The latest version of the standard 6.6 was released in 13 May 2025.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] The firmware-level ACPI has three main components: the ACPI tables, the ACPI BIOS, and the ACPI registers.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] The ACPI BIOS generates ACPI tables and loads ACPI tables into main memory.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Much of the firmware ACPI functionality is provided in bytecode of *ACPI Machine Language* (*AML*), a Turing-complete, domain-specific low-level language, stored in the ACPI tables.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] To make use of the ACPI tables, the operating system must have an interpreter for the AML bytecode.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] A reference AML interpreter implementation is provided by the *ACPI Component Architecture* (*ACPICA*).
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] At the BIOS development time, AML bytecode is compiled from *ACPI Source Language* (*ASL*) code.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] The **ACPI Component Architecture** (**ACPICA**), mainly written by Intel's engineers, provides an open-source platform-independent reference implementation of the operating system–related ACPI code.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] The ACPICA code is used by Linux, Haiku, ArcaOS and FreeBSD, which supplement it with their operating-system specific code.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] The first revision of the ACPI specification was released in December 1996, supporting 16, 24 and 32-bit addressing spaces.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] It was not until August 2000 that ACPI received 64-bit address support as well as support for multiprocessor workstations and servers with revision 2.0.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] In 1999, then Microsoft CEO Bill Gates stated in an e-mail that Linux would benefit from ACPI without them having to do work and suggested to make it Windows-only.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Released in June 2009, revision 4.0 of the ACPI specification added various new features to the design; most notable are the USB 3.0 support, logical processor idling support, and x2APIC support.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Initially ACPI was exclusive to x86 architecture; Revision 5.0 of the ACPI specification was released in December 2011, which added the ARM architecture support.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] The revision 5.1 was released in July 2014.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] The latest revision 6.6, which was released in May 2025, added the RISC-V support.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Microsoft's Windows 98 was the first operating system to implement ACPI, but its implementation was somewhat buggy or incomplete, although some of the problems associated with it were caused by the first-generation ACPI hardware.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Other operating systems, including later versions of Windows, macOS (x86 macOS only), eComStation, ArcaOS, FreeBSD (since FreeBSD 5.0), NetBSD (since NetBSD 1.6), OpenBSD (since OpenBSD 3.8), HP-UX, OpenVMS, Linux, GNU/Hurd and PC versions of Solaris, have at least some support for ACPI.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Some newer operating systems, like Windows Vista, require the computer to have an ACPI-compliant BIOS, and since Windows 8, the S0ix/Modern Standby state was implemented.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Windows operating systems use acpi.sys to access ACPI events.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] The 2.4 series of the Linux kernel had only minimal support for ACPI, with better support implemented (and enabled by default) from kernel version 2.6.0 onwards.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Old ACPI BIOS implementations tend to be quite buggy, and consequently are not supported by later operating systems.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] For example, Windows 2000, Windows XP, and Windows Server 2003 only use ACPI if the BIOS date is after January 1, 1999.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Similarly, Linux kernel 2.6 may not use ACPI if the BIOS date is before January 1, 2001.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Linux-based operating systems can provide handling of ACPI events via acpid.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Once an OSPM-compatible operating system activates ACPI, it takes exclusive control of all aspects of power management and device configuration.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] The OSPM implementation must expose an ACPI-compatible environment to device drivers, which exposes certain system, device and processor states.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] The specification also defines a *Legacy* state: the state of an operating system which does not support ACPI.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] In this state, the hardware and power are not managed via ACPI, effectively disabling ACPI.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] For describing the idle states of groupings of components (e.g. a package containing several cores), the _LPI (low power idle) method is used.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] This should not be confused with Intel's private LPIT table, used to describe S0ix sleep in package C10 or PCH SLP_S0 state.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] While a device or processor operates (D0 and C0, respectively), it can be in one of several power-performance states.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] These states are implementation-dependent.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] P0 is always the highest-performance state, with P1 to P*n* being successively lower-performance states.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] The total number of states is device or processor dependent, but can be no greater than 16.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] P-states have become known as SpeedStep in Intel processors, as PowerNow! or Cool'n'Quiet in AMD processors, and as PowerSaver in VIA processors.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] See Dynamic frequency scaling § Autonomous frequency scaling for a brief description of a newer control method based on the ACPI Collaborative Processor Performance Control (CPPC).
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] This new method allows hundreds of possible states, and for the processor to autonomously to choose from a given range of states.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] ACPI-compliant systems interact with hardware through either a "Function Fixed Hardware (FFH) Interface", or a platform-independent hardware programming model which relies on platform-specific ACPI Machine Language (AML) provided by the original equipment manufacturer (OEM).
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Function Fixed Hardware interfaces are platform-specific features, provided by platform manufacturers for the purposes of performance and failure recovery.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Standard Intel-based PCs have a fixed function interface defined by Intel, which provides a set of core functionality that reduces an ACPI-compliant system's need for full driver stacks for providing basic functionality during boot time or in the case of major system failure.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] ACPI Platform Error Interface (APEI) is a specification for reporting of hardware errors, e.g. chipset, RAM to the operating system.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] ACPI defines many tables that provide the interface between an ACPI-compliant operating system and system firmware (BIOS or UEFI).
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] This includes RSDP, RSDT, XSDT, FADT, FACS, DSDT, SSDT, MADT, and MCFG, for example.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] The tables allow description of system hardware in a platform-independent manner, and are presented as either fixed-formatted data structures or in AML.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] The main AML table is the DSDT (differentiated system description table).
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] The AML can be decompiled by tools like Intel's iASL (open-source, part of ACPICA) for purposes like patching the tables for expanding OS compatibility.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] The Root System Description Pointer (RSDP) is located in a platform-dependent manner, and describes the rest of the tables.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] A custom ACPI table called the Windows Platform Binary Table (WPBT) is used by Microsoft to allow vendors to add software into the Windows OS automatically.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Lenovo have been caught using this feature to install harmful software such as Superfish.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Also, Gigabyte Technology have been found using this feature to install its OEM software.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Samsung shipped PCs with Windows Update disabled.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Windows versions older than Windows 7 do not support this feature, but alternative techniques can be used.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] This behavior has been compared to rootkits.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] Ubuntu founder Mark Shuttleworth says ACPI is a security risk.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] He says "arguing for ACPI on your next-generation device is arguing for a trojan horse of monumental proportions to be installed in your living room and in your data centre" and "firmware on your device is the NSA's best friend".
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acpi] In November 2003, Linus Torvalds—author of the Linux kernel—described ACPI as "a complete design disaster in every way".
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] Acronis products support platforms such as Microsoft 365, Google Workspace, AWS, and Azure.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] Acronis was founded in 2003 in Singapore by Serg Bell as a spin-off from SWsoft (later known as Parallels), initially focusing on disk imaging and backup with its flagship product, Acronis True Image.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] It was incorporated in Switzerland in 2008.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] The company expanded through acquisitions, including GroupLogic in 2012, BackupAgent and nScaled in 2014.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] Further acquisitions included 5nine Software in 2019, and DeviceLock and CyberLynx in 2020.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] That same year, Acronis launched its Cyber Protect platform, integrating backup and cybersecurity.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] The company supports integrations with platforms such as ConnectWise and Microsoft Azure.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] In 2019, Acronis raised $147 million from Goldman Sachs, reaching a valuation of over $1 billion.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] A 2021 funding round of $250 million led by CVC Capital Partners increased its valuation to over $2.5 billion.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] In 2025, Acronis became majority-owned by EQT, a Swedish private equity firm headquartered in Stockholm.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] According to CEO Ezequiel Steiner, EQT's investment brings additional management "brain power" along with an enhanced understanding of the broader market, best practices, and benchmarking to Acronis.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] The acquisition is subject to federal regulatory approvals expected in 2025.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] Acronis maintains offices in North America, Europe, Asia, and the Middle East, with R&D centers in Bulgaria, the United States, Israel, and Singapore.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] It operates a global network of cloud data centers and supports over 20,000 service providers protecting approximately 750,000 businesses worldwide.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] On September 15, 2025, the US Director of National Intelligence ordered the exclusion and removal of all Acronis products and services from the Intelligence Community.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] This order applies per FAR Subpart 4.23 only to intelligence community and sensitive compartmented information systems.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] The DNI order is based on a Federal Acquisition Security Council (FASC) recommendation.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] However, neither FASC nor the DNI have identified any vulnerabilities within Acronis products or processes.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] The order does not prevent Acronis or its partners serving any customers besides the US intelligence community.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] As of 2025, Acronis’s executive leadership includes CEO Jan-Jaap Jager who replaced Ezequiel Steiner, and Chairman Warren Adelman.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/acronis-os-selector] Following EQT’s majority acquisition, EQT partner Johannes Reichel serves as a strategic Board representative.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] The company started as a manufacturer of complete motherboards, positioning itself in the high-end segment.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] Its first customer was PC's Limited, later known as Dell.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] As hardware activity moved progressively to Taiwan-based ODMs, AMI continued to develop BIOS firmware for major motherboard manufacturers.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] The company produced BIOS software for motherboards (1986), server motherboards (1992), storage controllers (1995) and remote management cards (1998).
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] In 1993, AMI produced MegaRAID, a storage controller card.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] AMI sold its RAID assets to LSI in 2001, with only one employee from the RAID-division remaining with the AMI core team.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] AMI continued to focus on OEM and ODM business and technology.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] From 2019 to 2026, HGGC, a private equity firm, held a significant stake in AMI, including leading the rebrand from American Megatrends to AMI.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] They announced their intent to sell in 2024 and in May 2026, American Megatrends entered into a definitive agreement to be acquired by Lattice Semiconductor for 1.65 billion in a combination of cash and stock.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] (AMI) was founded in 1985 by Subramonian Shankar and Pat Sarma with funds from a previous consulting venture, Access Methods Inc.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] Access Methods was a company run by Pat Sarma and his partner.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] After Access Methods successfully launched the AMIBIOS, there were legal issues among the owners of the company, resulting in Sarma buying out his partners.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] Access Methods still owned the rights to the AMIBIOS.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] Sarma had already started a company called Quintessential Consultants Inc.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] (QCI), and later set up an equal partnership with Shankar.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] By this time the AMIBIOS had become established and there was a need to keep the initials AMI.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] The partners renamed QCI as American Megatrends, with the same initials as Access Methods; the renamed company then purchased AMIBIOS from Access Methods.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] Shankar became the president and Sarma the executive vice-president of this company.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] This partnership continued until 2001, when LSI Logic purchased the RAID Division of American Megatrends; American Megatrends then purchased all shares of the company owned by Sarma, making Shankar the majority owner.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] AMIDiag is a family of PC diagnostic utilities sold to OEMs only.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] The AMIDiag suite was introduced in 1991 and made available for MS-DOS, Microsoft Windows and UEFI platforms.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] It includes both the Windows and DOS PC diagnostics programs.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] Later versions of AMIDiag support UEFI, which allows diagnostics to be performed directly on the hardware components, without having to use operating system drivers or facilities.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] Aptio V is AMI's current main UEFI firmware product.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] Aptio Community Edition is an open source UEFI firmware product.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] Aptio 4 is a now-discontinued previous version that has been succeeded by Aptio V.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] Aptio is usually used by the PC and server type devices.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] MegaRAC is a product line of BMC firmware packages and formerly service processors providing out-of-band, or lights-out remote management of computer systems.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] These BMCs running MegaRAC firmware packages or service processors operate independently of the operating system status or location, to manage and troubleshoot computers.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] AMIBIOS is the IBM PC-compatible BIOS that was formerly developed and sold by American Megatrends since 1986.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] In 1994, the company claimed that 75% of PC clones used AMIBIOS.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] It is used on motherboards made by AMI and by other companies.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] American Megatrends had a strict OEM business model for AMIBIOS: it sold source code to motherboard manufacturers or customized AMIBIOS for each OEM individually, whichever business model they require.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] AMI does not sell to end users, and itself produces no end-user documentation or technical support for its BIOS firmware, leaving that to licensees.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] However, the company published two books on its BIOS in 1993 and 1994, written by its engineers.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] During powerup, the BIOS firmware displays an ID string in the lower-left-hand corner of the screen.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] This ID string comprises various pieces of information about the firmware, including when it was compiled, what configuration options were selected, the OEM license code, and the targeted chipset and motherboard.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] There are 3 ID string formats, the first for older AMIBIOS, and the second and third for the newer AMI Hi-Flex ("high flexibility") BIOS.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] These latter are displayed when the Insert key is pressed during power-on self-test.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] The original AMI BIOS did not encrypt the machine startup password, which it stored in non-volatile RAM.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] Therefore, any utility capable of reading a PC's NVRAM was able to read and to alter the password.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] The AMI WinBIOS encrypts the stored password, using a simple substitution cipher.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] By pressing the Delete key during power-on self-test when a prompt is displayed, the BIOS setup utility program is invoked.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] Some earlier AMIBIOS versions also included a cut-down version of the AMIDIAG utility that AMI also sold separately, but most later AMI BIOSes do not include this program as the BIOS DMI already incorporates detailed diagnostics.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] AMIBIOS was formerly sold through distributors, not directly available from the manufacturer or from eSupport.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] AMI supplies both DOS and Windows firmware upgrade utilities for its own motherboards. eSupport only supplies a Windows upgrade utility.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] The StorTrends family of network-based backup and storage management software and hardware includes several NAS and iSCSI-based SAN servers with 4, 12, or 16 drive bays.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] AMI couples off-the-shelf hardware with the StorTrends iTX storage management firmware platform.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] StorTrends offers synchronous, asynchronous and snap-assisted replication, thin provisioning, high-availability grouping and advanced caching.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] Reliability and performance is the key for any storage server.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] StorTrends iTX 2.8 is designed to support Storage Bridge Bay specification that provide Auto-Failover capability to ensure that any interruption is handled without affecting data.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] It supports High-availability cluster, redundancy, scalability, replication, disaster recovery and multiple site backups.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] Because DuOS-M has the capability to run both Windows and Android simultaneously, the user can switch between the two operating systems without having to dual boot or suspend operation of one operating system in order to utilize the other.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] DuOS-M supports key hardware peripherals in Windows including cameras, audio, microphone and sensors such as ambient light sensor, accelerometer, gyrometer, compass and orientation sensors.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] It also supports various screen sizes, resolutions, and screen orientation (portrait and landscape) along with 3D acceleration and HD video playback.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] The first version of DuOS-M was released in June 2014.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] The software is available for download for a free 30-day trial, and is available for purchase for a complete license.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] On March 7, 2018, American Megatrends officially announced that it ceased development of DuOS-M.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] No further updates were being released at this time, including bug fixes and security patches.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] On November 13, 1993, some PCs with AMIBIOS firmware began bootup playing the tune to "Happy Birthday".
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] The PC would remain halted, and the song would continue playing until a key was pressed, after which bootup would resume.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] The problem was caused by a virus-free Trojan, which was later resolved with firmware updates.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] The AMI WinBIOS was a 1994 update to AMIBIOS, with a GUI setup screen that mimicked the appearance of Windows 3.1 and supported mouse navigation, unusual at the time.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] WinBIOS was viewed favorably by Anand Lal Shimpi at AnandTech, but described by Thomas Pabst at Tom's Hardware as a "big disappointment", in part because of problems with distributing IRQ signals to every PCI and ISA expansion slot.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] In July 2008 Linux developers discovered issues with ACPI tables on certain AMIBIOS BIOSes supplied by Foxconn, ASUS, and MSI.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] The problem was related to the ACPI _OSI method, which is used by ACPI to determine the OS version (in case an ACPI patch only applies to one specific OS).
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] In some cases, the OSI method caused problems on Linux systems, skipping code that was only executed on Windows systems.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] Foxconn and AMI worked together to develop a solution, which was included in later revisions of AMIBIOS.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] The issue affected motherboards with Intel Socket 775.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] Actual system behavior differed based on BIOS version, system hardware and Linux distribution.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/ami-aptio] In October 2021 an issue was discovered where some Baseboard Management Controllers were shipped with a license/royalty sticker that had the company name misspelled as "American Megatrands".
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] An **application programming interface** (**API**) is a connection between computers or between computer programs.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] It is a type of software interface, offering a service to other pieces of software.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] A document or standard that describes how to build such a connection or interface is called an *API specification*.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] A computer system that meets this standard is said to *implement* or *expose* an API.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The term API may refer either to the specification or to the implementation.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] In contrast to a user interface, which connects a computer to a person, an application programming interface connects computers or pieces of software to each other.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] It is not intended to be used directly by a person (the end user) other than a computer programmer who is incorporating it into software.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] An API is often made up of different parts which act as tools or services that are available to the programmer.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] A program or a programmer that uses one of these parts is said to *call* that portion of the API.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The calls that make up the API are also known as subroutines, methods, requests, or endpoints.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] An API specification *defines* these calls, meaning that it explains how to use or implement them.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] One of the main purpose of APIs is to hide the internal details of how a system works, exposing only those parts a programmer will find useful and keeping them consistent even if the internal details later change.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] An API may be custom-built for a particular pair of systems, or it may be a shared standard allowing interoperability among many systems.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The term API is often used to refer to web APIs, which allow communication between computers that are joined by the internet.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] There are also APIs for programming languages, software libraries, computer operating systems, and computer hardware.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] APIs originated in the 1940s, though the term did not emerge until the 1960s and 70s.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] An API opens a software system to interactions from the outside.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] It allows two software systems to communicate across a boundary — an interface — using mutually agreed-upon signals.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] In other words, an API connects software entities together.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Unlike a user interface, an API is typically not visible to users.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] It is an "under the hood" portion of a software system, used for machine-to-machine communication.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] A well-designed API exposes only objects or actions needed by software or software developers.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] This abstraction simplifies programming.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Building software using APIs has been compared to using building-block toys, such as Lego bricks.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Software services or software libraries are analogous to the bricks; they may be joined together via their APIs, composing a new software product.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The process of joining is called *integration*.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] As an example, consider a weather sensor that offers an API.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] When a certain message is transmitted to the sensor, it will detect the current weather conditions and reply with a weather report.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The message that activates the sensor is an API *call*, and the weather report is an API *response*.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] A weather forecasting app might integrate with a number of weather sensor APIs, gathering weather data from throughout a geographical area.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] It represents an agreement between parties: a service provider who offers the API and the software developers who rely upon it.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] If the API remains stable, or if it changes only in predictable ways, developers' confidence in the API will increase.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The term *API* initially described an interface only for end-user-facing programs, known as application programs.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] This origin is still reflected in the name "application programming interface." Today, the term is broader, including also utility software and even hardware interfaces.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The idea of the API is much older than the term itself.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] British computer scientists Maurice Wilkes and David Wheeler worked on a modular software library in the 1940s for EDSAC, an early computer.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The subroutines in this library were stored on punched paper tape organized in a filing cabinet.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] This cabinet also contained what Wilkes and Wheeler called a "library catalog" of notes about each subroutine and how to incorporate it into a program.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Today, such a catalog would be called an API (or an API specification or API documentation) because it instructs a programmer on how to use (or "call") each subroutine that the programmer needs.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Wilkes and Wheeler's book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer* contains the first published API specification.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Joshua Bloch considers that Wilkes and Wheeler "latently invented" the API, because it is more of a concept that is discovered than invented.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The term "application program interface" (without an *-ing* suffix) is first recorded in a paper called *Data structures and techniques for remote computer graphics* presented at an AFIPS conference in 1968.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The authors of this paper use the term to describe the interaction of an application—a graphics program in this case—with the rest of the computer system.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] A consistent application interface (consisting of Fortran subroutine calls) was intended to free the programmer from dealing with idiosyncrasies of the graphics display device, and to provide hardware independence if the computer or the display were replaced.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The term was introduced to the field of databases by C.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Date in a 1974 paper called *The Relational and Network Approaches: Comparison of the Application Programming Interface*.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] An API became a part of the ANSI/SPARC framework for database management systems.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] This framework treated the application programming interface separately from other interfaces, such as the query interface.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Database professionals in the 1970s observed these different interfaces could be combined; a sufficiently rich application interface could support the other interfaces as well.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] This observation led to APIs that supported all types of programming, not just application programming.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] By 1990, the API was defined simply as "a set of services available to a programmer for performing certain tasks" by technologist Carl Malamud.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The idea of the API was expanded again with the dawn of remote procedure calls and web APIs.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] As computer networks became common in the 1970s and 80s, programmers wanted to call libraries located not only on their local computers, but on computers located elsewhere.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] These remote procedure calls were well supported by the Java language in particular.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] In the 1990s, with the spread of the internet, standards like CORBA, COM, and DCOM competed to become the most common way to expose API services.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] XML and JSON web APIs saw widespread commercial adoption beginning in 2000 and continuing as of 2021.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The web API is now the most common meaning of the term API.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The Semantic Web proposed by Tim Berners-Lee in 2001 included "semantic APIs" that recast the API as an open, distributed data interface rather than a software behavior interface.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Proprietary interfaces and agents became more widespread than open ones, but the idea of the API as a data interface took hold.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Because web APIs are widely used to exchange data of all kinds online, API has become a broad term describing much of the communication on the internet.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] When used in this way, the term API has overlap in meaning with the term communication protocol.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The interface to a software library is one type of API.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The API describes and prescribes the "expected behavior" (a specification) while the library is an "actual implementation" of this set of rules.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] A single API can have multiple implementations (or none, being abstract) in the form of different libraries that share the same programming interface.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The separation of the API from its implementation can allow programs written in one language to use a library written in another.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] For example, because Scala and Java compile to compatible bytecode, Scala developers can take advantage of any Java API.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] API use can vary depending on the type of programming language involved.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] An API for a procedural language such as Lua could consist primarily of basic routines to execute code, manipulate data or handle errors while an API for an object-oriented language, such as Java, would provide a specification of classes and its class methods.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] By mapping the features and capabilities of one language to an interface implemented in another language, a language binding allows a library or service written in one language to be used when developing in another language.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Tools such as SWIG and F2PY, a Fortran-to-Python interface generator, facilitate the creation of such interfaces.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Moreover, the overall program flow of control can be out of the control of the caller and in the framework's hands by inversion of control or a similar mechanism.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] An API can specify the interface between an application and the operating system.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] POSIX, for example, specifies a set of common APIs that aim to enable an application written for a POSIX conformant operating system to be compiled for another POSIX conformant operating system.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Linux and Berkeley Software Distribution are examples of operating systems that implement the POSIX APIs.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Microsoft has shown a strong commitment to a backward-compatible API, particularly within its Windows API (Win32) library, so older applications may run on newer versions of Windows using an executable-specific setting called "Compatibility Mode".
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] How much Microsoft developers' access to the company's operating systems' internal APIs is an advantage is unclear.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Shaffer of *Technologic Computer Letter* in 1987 compared the situation to a baseball game in which "Microsoft owns all the bats and the field", and large vendors like Lotus Development and Ashton-Tate reportedly received information about MS-DOS 5.0 that smaller software developers did not.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Ed Esber of Ashton-Tate said in a 1987 interview, however, that Bill Gates told him that his developers sometimes had to rewrite software based on early APIs.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Gates noted in the interview that Microsoft's Apple Macintosh applications were more successful than those for MS-DOS, because his company did not have to also devote resources to Mac OS.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] An API differs from an application binary interface (ABI) in that an API is source code based while an ABI is binary based.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] For instance, POSIX provides APIs while the Linux Standard Base provides an ABI.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Remote APIs allow developers to manipulate remote resources through protocols, specific standards for communication that allow different technologies to work together, regardless of language or platform.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Therefore, remote APIs are useful in maintaining the object abstraction in object-oriented programming; a method call, executed locally on a proxy object, invokes the corresponding method on the remote object, using the remoting protocol, and acquires the result to be used locally as a return value.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] A modification of the proxy object will also result in a corresponding modification of the remote object.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Web APIs are the defined interfaces through which interactions happen between an enterprise and applications that use its assets, which also is a Service Level Agreement (SLA) to specify the functional provider and expose the service path or URL for its API users.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] An API approach is an architectural approach that revolves around providing a program interface to a set of services to different applications serving different types of consumers.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] An example might be a shipping company API that can be added to an eCommerce-focused website to facilitate ordering shipping services and automatically include current shipping rates, without the site developer having to enter the shipper's rate table into a web database.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Part of this trend is related to the Semantic Web movement toward Resource Description Framework (RDF), a concept to promote web-based ontology engineering technologies.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Web APIs allow the combination of multiple APIs into new applications known as mashups.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] In the social media space, web APIs have allowed web communities to facilitate sharing content and data between communities and applications.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] In this way, content that is created in one place dynamically can be posted and updated to multiple locations on the web.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] For example, Twitter's REST API allows developers to access core Twitter data and the Search API provides methods for developers to interact with Twitter Search and trends data.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The design of an API has significant impact on its usage.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The principle of information hiding describes the role of programming interfaces as enabling modular programming by hiding the implementation details of the modules so that users of modules need not understand the complexities inside the modules.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Thus, the design of an API attempts to provide only the tools a user would expect.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The design of programming interfaces represents an important part of software architecture, the organization of a complex piece of software.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] APIs are one of the more common ways technology companies integrate.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Those that provide and use APIs are considered as being members of a business ecosystem.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] An important factor when an API becomes public is its "interface stability".
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Changes to the API—for example adding new parameters to a function call—could break compatibility with the clients that depend on that API.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] When parts of a publicly presented API are subject to change and thus not stable, such parts of a particular API should be documented explicitly as "unstable".
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] For example, in the Google Guava library, the parts that are considered unstable, and that might change soon, are marked with the Java annotation `@Beta`.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] A public API can sometimes declare parts of itself as *deprecated* or rescinded.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] This usually means that part of the API should be considered a candidate for being removed, or modified in a backward incompatible way.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Therefore, these changes allow developers to transition away from parts of the API that will be removed or not supported in the future.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Client code may contain innovative or opportunistic usages that were not intended by the API designers.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] In other words, for a library with a significant user base, when an element becomes part of the public API, it may be used in diverse ways.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] On February 19, 2020, Akamai published their annual “State of the Internet” report, showcasing the growing trend of cybercriminals targeting public API platforms at financial services worldwide.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] From December 2017 through November 2019, Akamai witnessed 85.42 billion credential violation attacks.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] About 20%, or 16.55 billion, were against hostnames defined as API endpoints.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Of these, 473.5 million have targeted financial services sector organizations.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] API documentation describes what services an API offers and how to use those services, aiming to cover everything a client would need to know for practical purposes.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Documentation is crucial for the development and maintenance of applications using the API.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] API documentation is traditionally found in documentation files but can also be found in social media such as blogs, forums, and Q&A websites.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Traditional documentation files are often presented via a documentation system, such as Javadoc or Pydoc, that has a consistent appearance and structure.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] However, the types of content included in the documentation differs from API to API.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] In the interest of clarity, API documentation may include a description of classes and methods in the API as well as typical usage scenarios, code snippets, design rationales, performance discussions, and contracts, but implementation details of the API services themselves are usually omitted.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] It can take a number of forms, including instructional documents, tutorials, and reference works.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] It'll also include a variety of information types, including guides and functionalities.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Restrictions and limitations on how the API can be used are also covered by the documentation.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] For instance, documentation for an API function could note that its parameters cannot be null, that the function itself is not thread safe.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Because API documentation tends to be comprehensive, it is a challenge for writers to keep the documentation updated and for users to read it carefully, potentially yielding bugs.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] API documentation can be enriched with metadata information like Java annotations.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] This metadata can be used by the compiler, tools, and by the *run-time* environment to implement custom behaviors or custom handling.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] It is possible to generate API documentation in a data-driven manner.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] By observing many programs that use a given API, it is possible to infer the typical usages, as well the required contracts and directives.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Then, templates can be used to generate natural language from the mined data.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] In 2010, Oracle Corporation sued Google for having distributed a new implementation of Java embedded in the Android operating system.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Google had not acquired any permission to reproduce the Java API, although permission had been given to the similar OpenJDK project.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Judge William Alsup ruled in the *Oracle v.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Alsup's ruling was overturned in 2014 on appeal to the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, though the question of whether such use of APIs constitutes fair use was left unresolved.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] In 2016, following a two-week trial, a jury determined that Google's reimplementation of the Java API constituted fair use, but Oracle vowed to appeal the decision.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Oracle won on its appeal, with the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit ruling that Google's use of the APIs did not qualify for fair use.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] In 2019, Google appealed to the Supreme Court of the United States over both the copyrightability and fair use rulings, and the Supreme Court granted review.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the oral hearings in the case were delayed until October 2020.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/api] The case was decided by the Supreme Court in Google's favor.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/arc-specification] Although ACE went defunct, and no computer was ever manufactured which fully complied with the ARC standard, the ARC system has a widespread legacy in that all operating systems in the Windows NT family use ARC conventions for naming boot devices.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/arc-specification] SGI's modified version of the ARC firmware is named ARCS.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/arc-specification] All SGI computers which run IRIX 6.1 or later, such as the Indy and Octane, boot from an ARCS console, which uses the same drive naming conventions as Windows.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/arc-specification] Most of the various RISC-based computers designed to run Windows NT have versions of the ARC boot console to boot NT.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/arc-specification] It was predicted that Intel IA-32-based computers would adopt the ARC console, although only SGI ever marketed such machines with ARC firmware (namely, the SGI Visual Workstation series, which launched in 1999).
[src:preboot-execution-environment/arc-specification] Compared to UEFI, the ARC firmware also included support for FAT, boot variables, C-calling interface.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/arc-specification] It did not include the same level of extensibility as UEFI and the same level of governance like with the UEFI Forum.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/boot] In Unix-like operating systems, a **boot folder** is the directory which holds files used in booting the operating system, typically /boot.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/boot] The usage is standardized within Linux in the Filesystem Hierarchy Standard.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/boot] The contents are mostly Linux kernel files or boot loader files, depending on the boot loader, most commonly (on Linux) LILO or GRUB.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/boot] LILO may also use other files, such as message and also stores a non-boot configuration file in /etc/lilo.conf.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/boot] GRUB stores its files in the subdirectory grub/ (i.e. /boot/grub/).
[src:preboot-execution-environment/boot] These files are mostly modules (.mod), with configuration stored in grub.cfg.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/boot] /boot/ is often simply a directory on the main (or only) hard drive partition.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/boot] However, it may be a separate partition.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/boot] A separate partition is generally only used when bootloaders are incapable of reading the main filesystem (e.g.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/boot] LILO does not recognize XFS) or other problems not easily resolvable by users.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/boot] On UEFI systems, including most modern PCs, the EFI system partition is often mounted at /boot/, /efi/ or /boot/efi/.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] In computing, the **Preboot eXecution Environment** (**PXE**; often pronounced as /ˈpɪksiː/ *pixie*), often called **PXE boot** (*pixie boot*), is a specification describing a standardized client–server environment that boots a software assembly, retrieved from a network, on PXE-enabled clients.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] On the client side it requires only a PXE-capable network interface controller (NIC), and uses a small set of industry-standard network protocols such as Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) and Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP).
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The concept behind the PXE originated in the early days of protocols like BOOTP/DHCP/TFTP, and as of 2015 it forms part of the Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) standard.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] In modern data centers, PXE is the most frequent choice for operating system booting, installation and deployment.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] Since the beginning of computer networks, there has been a persistent need for client systems which can boot appropriate software images, with appropriate configuration parameters, both retrieved at boot time from one or more network servers.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] This goal requires a client to use a set of pre-boot services, based on industry standard network protocols.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] Additionally, the Network Bootstrap Program (NBP) which is initially downloaded and run must be built using a client firmware layer (at the device to be bootstrapped via PXE) providing a hardware independent standardized way to interact with the surrounding network booting environment.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] In this case the availability and subjection to standards are a key factor required to guarantee the network boot process system interoperability.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] One of the first attempts in this regard was bootstrap loading using TFTP standard RFC 906, published in 1984, which established the 1981 published Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) standard RFC 783 to be used as the standard file transfer protocol for bootstrap loading.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] It was followed shortly after by the Bootstrap Protocol standard RFC 951 (BOOTP), published in 1985, which allowed a diskless client machine to discover its own IP address, the address of a TFTP server, and the name of an NBP to be loaded into memory and executed.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] BOOTP implementation difficulties, among other reasons, eventually led to the development of the Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol standard RFC 2131 (DHCP) published in 1997.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The pioneering TFTP/BOOTP/DHCP approach fell short, as at the time, it did not define the required standardized client side of the provisioning environment.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The Preboot Execution Environment (PXE) was introduced as part of the Wired for Management framework by Intel and is described in the specification published by Intel and SystemSoft.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] PXE version 2.0 was released in December 1998, and the update 2.1 was made public in September 1999.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The PXE environment makes use of several standard client‑server protocols including DHCP and TFTP (now defined by the 1992 published RFC 1350).
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] Within the PXE schema the client side of the provisioning equation is an integral part of the PXE standard and it is implemented either as a Network Interface Card (NIC) BIOS extension or current devices in UEFI code.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The PXE relies on a combination of industry-standard Internet protocols, namely UDP/IP, DHCP and TFTP.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] These protocols have been selected because they are easily implemented in the client's NIC firmware, resulting in standardized small-footprint PXE ROMs.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] DHCP is used to provide the appropriate client network parameters and specifically the location (IP address) of the TFTP server hosting, ready for download, the initial bootstrap program (NBP) and complementary files.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] To initiate a PXE bootstrap session the DHCP component of the client's PXE firmware broadcasts a DHCPDISCOVER packet containing PXE-specific options to port 67/UDP (DHCP server port); it asks for the required network configuration and network booting parameters.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The PXE-specific options identify the initiated DHCP transaction as a PXE transaction.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] Standard DHCP servers (non PXE enabled) will be able to answer with a regular DHCPOFFER carrying networking information (i.e.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] IP address) but not the PXE specific parameters.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] A PXE client will not be able to boot if it only receives an answer from a non PXE enabled DHCP server.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] After parsing a PXE enabled DHCP server DHCPOFFER, the client will be able to set its own network IP address, IP Mask, etc., and to point to the network located booting resources, based on the received TFTP Server IP address and the name of the NBP.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The client next transfers the NBP into its own random-access memory (RAM) using TFTP, possibly verifies it (i.e.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] UEFI Secure Boot), and finally boots from it.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] NBPs are just the first link in the boot chain process and they generally request via TFTP a small set of complementary files in order to get running a minimalistic OS executive (i.e.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] WindowsPE, or a basic Linux kernel+initrd).
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The small OS executive loads its own network drivers and TCP/IP stack.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] At this point, the remaining instructions required to boot or install a full OS are provided not over TFTP, but using a robust transfer protocol (such as HTTP, CIFS, or NFS).
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The PXE Client/Server environment was designed so it can be seamlessly integrated with an already in place DHCP and TFTP server infrastructure.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] This design goal presented a challenge when dealing with the classic DHCP protocol.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] Corporate DHCP servers are usually subject to strict policies that are designed to prevent easily adding the additional parameters and rules required to support a PXE environment.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] For this reason the PXE standard developed the concept of DHCP redirection or "proxyDHCP".
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The proxyDHCP server providing TFTP server IP address and name of the NBP *only to PXE identified booting clients*.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] In a DHCP plus proxyDHCP server environment the PXE client initially broadcasts a single PXE DHCPDISCOVER packet and receives two complementary DHCPOFFERs; one from the regular non PXE enabled DHCP server and a second one from the proxyDHCP server.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] Both answers together provide the required information to allow the PXE client to continue with its booting process.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] This non-intrusive approach allows setting a PXE environment without touching the configuration of an already working DHCP server.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The proxyDHCP service may also run on the same host as the standard DHCP service but even in this case they are both two independently run and administered applications.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] Since two services cannot use the same port 67/UDP on the same host, the proxyDHCP runs on port 4011/UDP.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The proxyDHCP approach has proved to be extremely useful in a wide range of PXE scenarios going from corporate to home environments.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] PXE was conceived considering several system architectures.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The version 2.1 of the specification defined architecture identifiers for six system types, including IA-64 and DEC Alpha.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] However, PXE v2.1 only completely covered IA-32.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] Despite this apparent lack of completeness Intel has recently decided to widely support PXE within the new UEFI specification extending the PXE functionality to all EFI/UEFI environments.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] Current Unified Extensible Firmware Interface Specification 2.4A, Section 21 Network Protocols — SNP, PXE, and BIS defines the protocols that provide access to network devices while executing in the UEFI boot services environment.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] These protocols include the Simple Network Protocol (SNP), the PXE Base Code Protocol (PXE), and the Boot Integrity Services Protocol (BIS).
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] Today in a PXE environment the client architecture detection is rarely based on the identifiers originally included with the PXE v2.1 specification.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] Instead, each computer that will be booting from the network should have set DHCP option 93 to indicate the client's architecture.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] This enables a PXE server to know (at boot time) the exact architecture of the client from the first network boot packet.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] With the advent of IPv6, DHCP has evolved into DHCPv6; the need for options supporting PXE within the new DHCP protocol has been addressed in 2010.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The original PXE client firmware extension was designed as an Option ROM for the IA-32 BIOS, so a personal computer (PC) was originally made PXE-capable by installing a network interface controller (NIC) that provided a PXE Option ROM.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] Today the client PXE code is directly included within the NIC's own firmware or as part of the UEFI firmware on the motherboard.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] While Intel based ROMs have been implementing the client side of the PXE standard for more than 20 years some users were willing to trade extra features for stability and PXE standard conformance.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] PXE acceptance since v2.1 has been ubiquitous; today it is virtually impossible to find a network card without PXE firmware on it.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The availability of inexpensive Gigabit Ethernet hardware (NICs, switches, routers, etc.) has made PXE the fastest method available for installing an operating system on a client when competing against the classic CD, DVD, and USB flash drive alternatives.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] All the above-mentioned projects, when they are able to boot/install more than one OS, work under a "Boot Manager - Boot Loader" paradigm.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The initial NBP is a Boot Manager able to retrieve its own configuration and deploy a menu of booting options.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The user selects a booting option and an OS dependent Boot Loader is downloaded and run in order to continue with the selected specific booting procedure.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] Apple has come up with a very similar network boot approach under the umbrella of the Boot Server Discovery Protocol (BSDP) specification.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] BSDP v0.1 was initially published by Apple in August 1999 and its last v1.0.8 was published in September 2010.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] Mac OS X Server included a system tool called NetBoot.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] A NetBoot client uses BSDP to dynamically acquire resources that enable it to boot a suitable operating system.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] BSDP is crafted on top of DHCP using vendor-specific information to provide the additional NetBoot functionality not present in standard DHCP.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The protocol is implemented in client firmware.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] At boot time, the client obtains an IP address via DHCP then discovers boot servers using BSDP.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The client chooses an operating system from the list and sends a message to the server indicating its selection.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] The selected boot server responds supplying the boot file and boot image, and any other information needed to download and execute the selected operating system.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] Microsoft created a non-overlapping extension of the PXE environment with their Boot Information Negotiation Layer (BINL).
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] BINL is implemented as a server service and it is a key component of their Remote Installation Services (RIS) and Windows Deployment Services (WDS) strategies.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] It includes certain preparation processes and a network protocol that could be somehow considered a Microsoft-crafted DHCP extension.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] BINL is a Microsoft proprietary technology that uses PXE standard client firmware.
[src:preboot-execution-environment/preboot-execution-environment] Currently there is not a publicly available BINL specification.
